<encodingDesc n="1.5">
<projectDesc><p>This transcription was made by the Verbum Project as part of an online and printed edition of the Old Latin versions of John between 2005 and 2010.</p></projectDesc>
<editorialDecl><p>Only this lection is transcribed, from J Cozza "Sacrorum Bibliorum vetustissima fragmenta..." Rome: Joseph Spithoever 1867 p.336. It may be a palimpsest. This lection was read in both Greek and Latin on Easter Day. The first 14 verses correspond to the Vulgate; the remaining lines appear to have been translated by a mediaeval translator using a glossary.The transcription is taken from Cozza's edition. The initial transcription file was a plain text file for use with COLLATE. Further information about the procedures followed may be found in the electronic edition at <ptr target="http://www.iohannes.com/vetuslatina/"/></p>
<p>This second edition of the file was converted to XML by Catherine Smith using the project's Python conversion scripts 1.0.</p>
<p>The XML specifications used are version 1.5 of the IGNTP Guidelines available at <ptr target="http://epapers.bham.ac.uk/1892/"/></p></editorialDecl></encodingDesc>

